issue.body:
values are not updated in Gauge.builder

method.updateApplication() pull data from db

here code example:


  ```
public void registerApplicationSomeData() {
        String gaugeName =  "application-date";
        method.updateApplication().forEach(bucket -> {
            Tags tags = Tags.of("tags.some-tag", bucket.Type());
            Optional.ofNullable(register.find(gaugeName).tags(tags).gauge())
                    .ifPresent(gauge -> {
                        if (gauge.value() != bucket.count()) {
                            register.removeByPreFilterId(gauge.getId());
                        }
                    });
            Gauge.builder(gaugeName, bucket::count)
                    .description("Some description")
                    .tags(tags)
                    .register(register);
        });
    }

```

I expect that the data will be update but after initialization  the gauge does not update the value and that is why i have to add optional remove (it is works) which is not good solution for performance. I use  Gauge.builder(gaugeName, bucket,  bk-> bucket.count()) and a lot of suggestions here and Stackoverflow  and so on but in my case  it does not work. And I know about Multi-gauge (work for db) but it does not appropriate in my case
if i use for example  Gauge.builder(gaugeName, bucket,  bk->new Random().getInt()) the value is update

When running the following code:

```java
public void testGauge(MeterRegistry meterRegistry) {
   // Creating the Gauge
   AtomicInteger value1 = meterRegistry.gauge("myTestGauge", new AtomicInteger(0));

   // Getting the same Gauge
   AtomicInteger value2 = meterRegistry.gauge("myTestGauge", new AtomicInteger(1));

   value1.set(2);
   value2.set(3);

   System.out.println(meterRegistry.get("myTestGauge").gauge().value());  
}
```

I get a value of 2 - when I would expect a value of 3.

It appears that the underlining code for meterRegistry.gauge checks to see if the Gauge already exists and if so uses that Gauge in the code internally. However, the method always returns the reference object you pass in - while not updating the Gauge's reference.
Wouldn't this be problematic when actually calling value2.set(3). Wouldn't that set not get monitored - as no Gauge is technically referencing it?

It would be nice to have a method where we present a value if the Gauge is not present. If the Gauge is present, it should just return back the reference object for the Gauge.

Thanks,
-Dave

